      <hedline>
        <hl1>Rookies at the Wheels</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By John Shaw</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Shaw, John</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Olympic organizers are concerned about Sydney's buses as 750 new drivers, new routes and changing schedules cause delays and no-shows; Olympics Min Michael Knight holds size of task was underestimated (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>First it was Sydney's trains that troubled Olympic organizers, but now with the railroad mostly running on time, it is the city's buses that are making the officials anxious.</p>
        <p>''It is clear the size of the task has been underestimated; we need more drivers,'' said Olympics Minister Michael Knight, a man not noted for apologies.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>First it was Sydney's trains that troubled Olympic organizers, but now with the railroad mostly running on time, it is the city's buses that are making the officials anxious.</p>
        <p>''It is clear the size of the task has been underestimated; we need more drivers,'' said Olympics Minister Michael Knight, a man not noted for apologies.</p>
        <p>The 750 new drivers, the new routes and the changing schedules are causing delays and no-shows on Olympic shuttles.</p>
        <p>These new services link the athletes and media villages to training sites and media centers, and they ferry Games officials, national delegates and team coaches back and forth to hotels, meetings and arenas.</p>
        <p>Australian and International Olympic Committee officials define the bus woes as the usual pre-Games ''teething problems.''</p>
        <p>John Shaw</p>
        <p>OLYMPICS: NOTEBOOK</p>
      </block>
